SIMPLE: stud
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stud
<hw>Stud</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>stod</ets>,
<ets>stood</ets>, AS. <ets>st⟦omac⟧d</ets>; akin to OHG.
<ets>stuota</ets>, G. <ets>stute</ets> a mare, Icel.
<ets>st⟦omac⟧<?/</ets> stud, Lith. <ets>stodas</ets> a herd, Russ.
<ets>stado</ets>, and to E. <ets>stand</ets>. The sense is properly, a
stand, an establishment. ⟦root⟧163. See <er>Stand</er>, and cf.
<er>Steed</er>.]</ety> <def>A collection of breeding horses and mares,
or the place where they are kept; also, a number of horses kept for a
racing, riding, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the <qex>studs</qex> of Ireland, where care is taken, we see
horses bred of excellent shape, vigor, and size.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had the finest <qex>stud</qex> in England, and his delight was
to win plates from Tories.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stud</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stud
<hw>Stud</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>studu</ets> a
post; akin to Sw. <ets>st⟦oum⟧d</ets> a prop, Icel. <ets>sto<?/</ets> a
post, <ets>sty<?/ja</ets> to prop, and probably ultimately to E.
<ets>stand</ets>; cf. D. <ets>stut</ets> a prop, G.
<ets>st⟦uum⟧tze</ets>. See <er>Stand</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
stem; a trunk.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Seest not this same hawthorn <qex>stud</qex>?</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>An upright scanting, esp. one of
the small uprights in the framing for lath and plaster partitions, and
furring, and upon which the laths are nailed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A kind of nail with a large head, used chiefly for
ornament; an ornamental knob; a boss.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A belt of straw and ivy buds,⟦br⟧
With coral clasps and amber <qex>studs</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Marlowe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Crystal and myrrhine cups, embossed with gems⟦br⟧
And <qex>studs</qex> of pearl.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An ornamental button of various forms, worn in a
shirt front, collar, wristband, or the like, not sewed in place, but
inserted through a buttonhole or eyelet, and transferable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A short rod or pin,
fixed in and projecting from something, and sometimes forming a
journal.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A stud bolt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>An iron brace across the shorter diameter of the
link of a chain cable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stud bolt</b></col>, <cd>a bolt with threads on both
ends, to be screwed permanently into a fixed part at one end and receive
a nut upon the other; -- called also <altname>standing
bolt</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stud</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stud
<hw>Stud</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Studded</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Studding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To adorn with
shining studs, or knobs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy horses shall be trapped,⟦br⟧
Their harness <qex>studded</qex> all with gold and pearl.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To set with detached ornaments or prominent objects;
to set thickly, as with studs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sloping sides and summits of our hills, and the extensive
plains that stretch before our view, are <qex>studded</qex> with
substantial, neat, and commodious dwellings of freemen.</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Hobart.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Studbook</ent>⟦br⟧
